-  the small and medium scale millers and stockists contribute largely to the process of offering a government guaranteed price for paddy farmers and providing rice to consumers at an affordable price through purchasing paddy and also processing and distributing rice.  The monthly consumption of rice in the country is around 180,000 mt. and the small and medium scale millers and stockists have the capacity to produce 60% of the market requirement.  The Government intends to strengthen the small and medium scale millers and stockists financially and to provide immediate relief to settle their outstanding loans during the past due to natural calamities and loss of harvest.   Accordingly, the following proposals made by H.E. the President, in his capacity as the Minister of Finance and Planning, were approved by the Cabinet: 
  
*	to suspend legal action taken by State Banks against the defaulted pledge loans of small and medium scale millers and stockists;

*	to write off the outstanding loan balances of pledge loans for paddy purchasing obtained by them from  State Banks during the period from 1997 to 2010 and for the General Treasury to provide the required funds to the relevant banks;

*	to offer a grace period of six (06) months with effect from 2015?01?01 for the repayment of the pledge loans granted by State Banks for paddy purchasing in Maha 2013/2014 and Yala 2014;

*	to purchase Samba rice and other rice stocks processed by them, through Lanka Sathosa Limited at Rs.85/- and Rs.82/- per kg. respectively and to provide financial facilities to Lanka Sathosa Limited in this regard;


*	to provide transformers free of charge for them, considering their electricity capacity requirement and to bear the cost of same by the Government; and

*	to implement a new Loan Scheme for them with concessionary  interest rates to improve the paddy purchasing and storage capacity and to improve the quality of rice through introduction of modern technology.

- the following sections of roads which link the Provinces and Districts of the country have been identified for rehabilitation, and improvement of these roads will provide better accessibility to the rural areas and will enhance the connectivity of productive centers to the domestic and international markets: 
*	Ayagama - Kukulegama Road - 16.89 km;
*	Dickwella - Jangulla - Thalpitigala Road - 24.14 km;
*	Balangoda - Bowatte - Kaltota Road - 28.96 km;
*	Norwood - Bogawanthalawa - Campian Road 16.89 km; 
*	Passara - Hingurukaduwa - Pelawatte Road - 30.17 km; and
*	Blackpool - Ambewella - Pattipola - Horton Plains Road 28.16 km.

	The proposal made by H.E. the President, in his capacity as the Minister of Highways, Ports and Shipping, to award the contract for the rehabilitation of the above road sections as recommended by the Standing Cabinet Appointed Procurement Committee (SCAPC), was approved by the Cabinet.

- the Government has given high priority for the construction of the portion of the Northern Expressway from Enderamulla to Galewela and the portion of the Link Expressway from Pothuhera to Galagedara. The proposal made by H.E. the President, in his capacity as the Minister of Highways, Ports and Shipping, to award the contracts for the following contract packages 02 to 06 for the construction of the Northern Expressway from Veyangoda to Galewela as recommended by the Standing Cabinet Appointed Procurement Committee (SCAPC), was approved by the Cabinet: 

		*	package 02 - Veyangoda - Meerigama (16.0 km);
		*	package 03 - Meerigama - Nakalagamuwa (18.0 km);
		*	package 04 - Nakalagamuwa - Alakoladeniya (20.1 km);
		*	package 05 - Alakoladeniya - Meddekatiya (16.9 km); and
		*	package 06 - Meddekatiya - Galewela (19.0 km).

the proposal made by Hon. Wimal Weerawansa, Minister of Construction, Engineering Services, Housing and Common Amenities, to expend a sum of Rs.15.6 million for the renovation of housing units under the National Housing Development Authority and to meet the  housing needs of the low income community in the city of Colombo and for the implementation of  the undermentioned projects aimed at offering a better living standard to the people living in the relevant areas, was approved by the Cabinet:

*	renovation of housing units under the National Housing Development Authority at a cost of Rs.5.6 million; and;

*	development of infrastructure facilities of the under-served settlements in the city of Colombo at a cost of Rs.10 million.

- the proposal made by Hon. (Dr.) Jagath Balasuriya, Minister of National Heritage, to establish the above fund, utilizing Rs.100 million approved in the Budget Proposals for 2012 as an initial capital of the fund, was approved by the Cabinet. The main objectives of establishing the above fund are as follows:

*	preservation of  archeological sites etc. of historical value;

* 	exploration and excavation of archeological sites and conservation of old paintings;

*	promotion of our heritage and provision of related information for foreign as well as local tourists; and

*	organization of exhibitions, printing of publications, production of audio-visual documentaries, conducting of workshops etc. to enhance the knowledge of the people regarding the preservation of archeological heritage for the future generation.

- the proposal made by H.E. the President, in his capacity as the Minister of Finance and Planning, to hold a Tax Week annually in order to create awareness among the public in respect of the Government Tax System and to declare the Tax Week from 01st to 08th November 2012, was approved by the Cabinet.  Its main objectives are as follows:

*	increase the awareness of the tax system among the public;

*	building public confidence in tax administration and related activities of the Departments of Inland Revenue and Sri Lanka Customs, whereby voluntary compliance with the taxes by the public could be encouraged;

*	enlighten the public of the contribution they could render towards future prosperity of the country through timely payment of taxes;

*	make the public aware of the tax reliefs and tax holidays granted by the new tax system which is being implemented since 2011;

- Cabinet considered  the recommendations of the Officials' Committee appointed for the purpose and approval was granted to implement the following recommendations of the Committee:

*	identification and mapping of fire prone areas in each District and preparation of Fire Management Plans for such areas;

*	supply of required resources, through the respective District Secretaries, to the Forest Department and the Department of Wildlife Conservation to ensure effective fire control programmes;

*	to advise the law enforcement authorities (Police and Armed Forces) to be vigilant, specially during the dry season, in order  to apprehend those responsible for initiating forest fires; and

*	conduct training and awareness programmes on fire management for communities and relevant stakeholders in the areas,

- theproposal made by  H.E. the President, in his capacity as the Minister of Defence and Urban Development,  to implement the following projects in stages, was approved by the Cabinet: 

*	refurbishment of Old Dutch Hospital building at Colombo Fort;
*	renovation work of Old Marketing Department Building at Colombo Fort; 
*	development of Race Course Grounds and Bloomfield Grounds;
*	refurbishment of Central Super Market, Pettah (former fish market);
*	development of Independence Square;
*	re-location of Manning Market to Peliyagoda; 
*	re-development of existing Manning Market premises for the expansion of bus stand and to accommodate informal sector within a Commercial Complex area.   
	The construction work of these projects will be entrusted to the Engineering 	Services Divisions of the Sri Lanka Army, Navy and Air Force so that the cost of 	construction could be kept to a minimum.

- after the conflict situation in the North, steps have been taken by the Ceylon Electricity Board to commence the Kilinochchi-Chunnakam Transmission Line.  The project consists of -

*	Construction of Chunnakam 132 KV Grid Substation - contract awarded (funded by ADB);

*	Construction of Kilinochchi-Chunnakam Transmission Line - contract awarded (funded by ADB);

*	Consultancy for Designing and Supervision - contract awarded (funded by KfW of Germany); and

		*	Upgrading 220 KV Protection Developm

	The proposal made by Hon. Patali Chanpika Ranawaka, Minister of Power and Energy, to award the contract for Earth Wire Replacement with OPGW, which is part of the contract of Upgrading 220 KV Protection Development, on the recommendation of the Standing Cabinet Appointed Procurement Committee, at a total cost of Euro 1,279,011.74 plus Sri Lanka Rs.26,335,080.00, was approved by the Cabinet

- the Eastern University consists of 05 Faculties established for Agriculture, Science, Arts and Culture, Commerce and Management and Healthcare Sciences, including the Campuses at Trincomalee and Swami Vipulananda Institute of Aesthetic Studies, Batticaloa and has a student population of a little over 3500. 	The following projects have been approved by the Cabinet for implementation:>br>

*	Building Complex for the Library;

*	Building Complex for the Faculty of Commerce and Management;

*	Building Complex for the Zoology Department/Faculty of Science; and,

*	Building Complex for the Faculty of Arts and Culture. 

	The proposal made by Hon. S.B. Dissanayake, Minister of Higher Education, to revise the total cost estimates of the 04 projects and to regularize the appointment of the Central Engineering Consultancy Bureau as Consultant and Construction Contractor, was approved by the Cabinet.  The construction work will be done with funds provided in the 2012 Budget Estimates and those to be provided under the Medium Term Budgetary Framework 2013 - 2014.

- the objective of the Government is to provide for the effective manner, administration and revival of these enterprises in the national interest, which are listed in the Schedules to the Act No.43 of 2011.  It has been observed that most of the enterprises related to the above have obtained many BOI concessions, and had not fulfilled the assurances given to the BOI, such as further investments, ensuring exports etc.  The proposal made by H.E. the President, in his capacity as the Minister of  Finance and Planning to appoint -


(a)	a Ministerial Committee consisting of the following and an Officials' Committee consisting of six Officials to assist this Committee, to ensure the overall monitoring of the related aspects in a timely manner:


*	Hon. Anura Priyadharshana Yapa, Minister of Environment - (Chairman);
*	Hon.  Dilan Perera, Minister of Foreign Employment and Welfare (Member);
*	Hon. Reginald Cooray, Minister of Minor Export Crop Promotion 	(Member);
*	Hon. Lakshman Seneviratne, Minister of Productivity Promotion 	(Member); and
*	Hon. Geethanjana Gunawardena, Deputy Minister of Finance and 	Planning (Member); and


(b)	the following Competent Authorities -

(i)	Lanka Tractors Limited (Properties situated at Pettah and Narahenpita), Charmers Granaries (Property situated at Pettah), Ceylinco Leisure Properties Ltd. (Properties situated at Kollupitiya, Colomb 3) and Intertrade Lanka (Private) Limited (Property situated at Fort, Colombo) - Mr. Kalinga Indatissa, Attorney-at-Law;

(ii)	Hotel Developers Lanka plc (HDL) - Mr. Senaka Walgampaya, Attorney-at-Law;

(iii)	Pelwatte Sugar Industries Ltd. - District Secretary, Hambantota;

(iv)	Sevanagala Sugar Industries Ltd. - District Secretary, Moneragala;

(v)	Colombo Commercial Company Limited (Badulla Property) - District Secretary, Badulla; and,

(vi)	all the remainder of Under Utilized Assets (being closed BOI Factories) - Mr. Tuly Cooray; 

was approved by the Cabinet.

- the proposal made by Hon. Mahinda Yapa Abeywardena, Minister of Agriculture to enter into a Memorandum of Understanding with the Rural Development Administration in the Republic of Korea to establish a Korean Project for International Agriculture Centre in Sri Lanka, was approved by the Cabinet.  The following programmes are to be implemented under this MOU: 



*	Agricultural Research and Development Projects agreed upon by both parties ;

*	Training activities of Sri Lankan farmers and Sri Lankan Researchers ;

*	Exchange of research inputs, publications and other technical information ; and 

*	Other activities of mutual interest.

- tea industry in Sri Lanka provides direct and indirect employment to around 1.5 million people in the country.  Contribution of tea to the total export earnings of Sri Lanka in 2010 was 15.6% which is an increase of 16.1% over the previous year.  Sri Lanka is the largest exporter of orthodox black tea which is globally known as Ceylon Tea. Due its superior characteristics, it is the most expensive black tea in the world. Hon. Mahinda Samarasinghe, Minister of Plantation Industries presented a Strategic Plan for a promotional campaign on Ceylon Tea for the period from 2012 to 2016 which was approved by the Cabinet.  This Plan expects to - 

*	sustain the current demand for Ceylon Tea in vulnerable markets and increase demand in potential markets;
*	rebuild the image of Pure Ceylon Tea and create the environment to reach the consumer;
*	create awareness at consumer level on "Lion Logo" Trade Mark; and
*	enhance demand for Pure Ceylon Tea packed in Sri Lanka and marketed globally.
